\ProvidesFile{ismej.bbx}[biblatex style for The ISME Journal]

%% Notes:
% 1. biblatex style for the ISME Journal. According to the Instructions for Authors (http://mts-isme.nature.com/cgi-bin/main.plex?form_type=display_auth_instructions)
% 2. This style is based on geb.bbx by Timoth√©e Poisot (https://github.com/tpoisot/ecobiblatex)
% 3. This style is intended to work with the biber processor. For instance, the journal abbreviations functionality (see below) cannot be achieved using bibtex. 
% 4. Journal abbreviation is not a standard bibtex field. Abbreviation of journal names can be achieved however in two ways using a special biber.conf file in XML format or using the \DeclareSourcemap command (biblatex 2.2 and above). For more info see: http://tex.stackexchange.com/questions/76241/show-journal-abbreviation-in-reference-list-with-biblatex-biber?rq=1
% 5. To deal with journal abbreviations I've prepared an additional file with search and replace strings for some 50+ journals and their abbreviations. This file should be placed in the same directory as the LaTeX document. Naturally there are many other journals which I did not include but the file should be easily edited to extend the list (notice though that each journal should be inserted twice -- once using `\step[ fieldsource = journal,` and the other time using `\step[ fieldsource = journaltitle,`.
% 6. According to ISME J reference style, multiple citations should be sorted by year (e.g. (Pugsley, 1996; Matsunaga et al., 1997)) which conflicts with the alphabetical sorting in the references. The solution is to use \printbibliography[sorting=nyt] in the document.
% 7. This style defines explicitly the formatting of only the following reference types: article, book and incollection. Other types are too rare and in any case are not formally described in the ISMEJ author guidelines..
% 8. This citation style is unofficial, and supplied 'as is' with no warranty whatsoever. i.e. don't blame me if you get an angry mail from the journal production office :)

